    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's an interesting way to put it. but if you look at the long term, a lot of people say that by removing Gaddafi, the coalition actually made the whole region way less stable and more prone to extremist groups, which is kind of the opposite of what they wanted. so if the \"victory\" in Benghazi actually caused a decade of chaos and terrorism, does the \"strategic success\" argument actually hold up, or is it just a way to justify mistakes?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
